              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It matters at the extremes: zero occurrences of your target keyword is problematic, and unnaturally high repetition triggers spam filters. In between, Google's algorithms rely on semantic understanding (BERT, MUM) and topical authority far more than raw keyword frequency.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I calculate keyword density?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Divide the number of times your keyword appears by the total word count of the page, then multiply by 100. Example: a 1,000-word article with the keyword appearing 12 times has a 1.2% keyword density.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What happens if keyword density is too high?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Excessive keyword repetition is classified as keyword stuffing by Google. It reads as unnatural, degrades user experience, and can trigger a manual or algorithmic penalty that drops rankings. Google's spam policies explicitly prohibit stuffing keywords into content or meta tags.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is TF-IDF the same as keyword density?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) compares how often a term appears on your page relative to how often it appears across a large corpus of documents. Keyword density is a simpler raw percentage. TF-IDF gives a more context-aware signal and is closer to how modern search engines evaluate term importance.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

